segments.text: the background here at A&M, that coming here from Ithaca right away to teach, I had to give up my, what I had begun on our Long Island as a soil surveyor, which Dr. Lyon said I really needed.
And Dr. W.T.
Carter, who was the soil, held the position of
the division of soil survey for the state of Texas and produced the first fine soil map of Texas and the discussion and description of the soil types and soil series of Texas.
He took me in hand and not only took me but my graduate students and me into the major soil divisions of Texas and supervise and super and conducted our

our investigation of the Maine soil regions and how to make, which was then very well-recognized in 19 and 26, the soil profile, 27 and right on up through 1934 when we had a soil... We had the soil...
Science in the federal branch in 1935 changed to soil conservation service.
Soil erosion service for one year and then changed to soil service, soil conservation.
And I took at the cooperation and suggestion of Dean Kyle and and Garb and Merrill, Lewis P. Merrill,
was able to spend the summer of 1934 in the Soil Conservation Service near Tyler in Smith County.
In the summer of 1934.
Depression was being felt pretty strongly at A&M.
And most teachers took a cut of around 30%.
And our first child, our second child was born that year.
And due to family background, I took my wife to Temple
to give birth to the child at Scott and White Hospital in Grover, but her college station twice a week to help Dr. J.O.
Morgan on the laboratory.
Dr. Morgan was then beginning to feel the result of his night and day work when he worked on his PhD at Cornell.
He got tooth trouble and he died later in 33.
And then a job was offered at Prairie View, teaching soils there, which I was very glad to have in that summer of 1930.
When I came back, Fred Hale, who was a meat cutting man, an animal husbandry expert, looked at my hand and said, well, Lucy, you haven't turned black yet.
When you were on the faculty, say from 27 on, did you live on campus, in campus housing?
Yes.
We, 26 to 27, we rented one of the new houses from Dr. Weasley Clark's College Station Development Association south of the campus.
In the fall of 27, Thomas F. Mayo, librarian, encouraged my wife and me to sublet his house on the campus next to the hospital.
In the fall of 28, the faculty committee on housing awarded us rental of a house behind what was then
The Steel Stadium next to Professor Ness.
Had some valuable association in those years.
Was the Steel Stadium located in the same place as the current Kyle Field?
Yes.
When it was dismantled in the summer of 29, then they moved our house down to a place right
looking upon the beginning of the 100-yard dash.
What was in the 100-yard dash straight away.
What type of house were you in?
Frame house, which had previously been part of the old hospital.
The other half was the one that had been used on the campus by Dr. Mayo.
Did you continue to live on campus through all of your teaching career, or at what point did you move off?
We lived on campus until the rule came up in 1941 that nobody, be he dean or be he an instructor, should continue to live on the campus in a campus house.
We built a house then.
present location in a five-acre tract, later a 26-acre tract, which we developed.
Was that 41 or 51?
But there were still houses on the campus for a good long while, actually.
For certain groups, such as the electrician and the librarian
the sewer, such as required night.
They were primarily staff instead of faculty.
Yes, sir.
Was there a considerable amount of socializing among the families who lived in those houses?
Quite so.
But due to A&M, even then, was one of the most
pleasant places that I had ever been.

In fact, when I got out of the Army and came down and rented a room in the YMCA and looked out of the back room onto Military Walk and saw the students doing the setting up exercises at 7 a.m., decided that this was the place that I wanted to be in my future.
And speaking of housing, I'm reminded of another question I meant to ask you earlier.
While you were
working on your master's at Texas A&M in, what, 1919 and 1920 and 21.
Where did you live at that point?
I'd gotten out of the Army until the fall of...
1919, I lived in the old Shirley Hotel, which were two frame buildings and offered not only housing but good food.
And the Shirley Hotel then was torn down later to make way for the Aggieland Inn.
In the fall of 1919, in September, I was able to get into Milner Hall with
W. William P. Derrick, who later became animal husbandry chief at Nebraska University, University of Nebraska.

And I had to go from there to the second year in graduate work and lived in Gallegate Hall, where we found out what it was, what was meant by the entomological ability to make the dormitories entirely free.
of anything that might molest a sleeper.
Milner Hall was always a delightful dormitory to me.
Were there all graduate students living in Milner Hall?
No, it was mixed then.
Mixed.
What about when you moved to Leggett?
Was it also mixed?
Mostly undergraduates, but my roommate there was a graduate student too, who later went to Brazil to the Presbyterian Church to introduce agronomy, agronomic work in Brazil.
Where did you have your meals?
We were fortunate to be able to eat in Speza Hall.
But I take it since you were not military, you did not have to march in with the... No sir, we ate in what was called the civilian, they didn't call them civilians, they called them another name.
At one point they called them casuals.
Casuals, yes.
So you had a separate dining area within Sevesa for the...
Yes, yes.
Okay.
I believe I picked up from a newspaper clipping in our files that you served a number of years on the College Station City Council.
Yes, I was on the initial organization where we met in the chemistry building lecture room in, to the best of my recollection, in October 19, I know the year definitely, 1938.
It was either spring or the fall of 1938 and resolved that we didn't have but one road to get to Bryan.
And I had been pointed, had been pointed to committee to see if we could get what is now College Main Street graveled so we could get to Bryan easier.
And the county
And the judge said, where's the money coming from?
And I said, from the county sources, or perhaps Brian can furnish a little to help get that trade into Brian.
And this, you can put this in or not as you want.
And said, we can't spend money on that.
So we met, we got together and said we needed another grocery store.

We had one Luke Patronell and Charlie Northgate and organized a video college station and without pay for anybody, John Henry Binney was the mayor and Wheeler Bargo was made the county, the city attorney and we gave
Jack Boyd, the honorary distinction of being the deputy.
And we each sparked up a little and got a deposit in the bank, I think, of $70.
You mentioned that you only had one road.
We had to go and follow the railroad track on what is now Old College Road.
And that's the one you wanted to have graveled?
We had a piece of...
Yes, we wanted that road graveled.
Because what is now College of Maine didn't extend beyond the... what is now the... complex of apartment houses.
Okay.
About 200 yards.
Uh-huh.
That is the four-lane portion of College Main that runs between Skag Albertson's and the Collegeville apartments.
Didn't exist.
That didn't exist.
That came into existence under Chancellor Gilchrist.
And I remember that distinctly because I was on advisory committee and the
the ones the county wanted to build the road to directly enter Abazel, what do you know, Abazel Street.
And Mr. Giltrist stated that that might not fit too well into the campus plans that were already made.
And it was opened up then.
into the present location.
It almost coincides.
Did, you indicated that...
I was also on the school board for the Consolidated School in, I think in the year 19 and
Cofer and Mitchell.
John Mitchell decided that we needed to transfer to have a school outside of the A&M campus, which was meeting then in old Pfeiffer Hall and that wooden building adjacent.
And he made the rounds from different people
to try to get enough to buy a little piece of land where we could have a school.
And at that time, among other activities, I was one of the competitors for the open handball competition we held, so-called championship.
And Mr. Colfer and Mr. Mitchell walked all the way down to the old handball courts, which were in that wooden building.
and asked me if I'd contribute to buying that old piece of ground.
And I think I gave him what was the end of, what we thought was the end of the Depression, $200.
And Mr. Cashin then headed, that was treasurer, and went over and bought that piece of land from the, uh, um, Dowborough Valleys and the, uh,

that's where the current where the original school is now what's um or it's still what the three-story where the three-story brick building is that faces jersey street yes sir it's not it's not three-story though is it two two well it does well to be a good one and a half uh-huh
Well, it was the middle school a couple years ago.
Now the middle school's moved across the street where the high school used to be by the football stadium there.
Well, that's where our first teaching place was.
Now, where?
You mean where the...
The so-called hunk of land going out Bissell Street, isn't it, into Jersey?
You come right into what was the first piece of land for the school.
Mm-hmm.
And various citizens were allowed to volunteer to put in the pavement of the sidewalks, which Dr. A.
A. Dunlap and I did a lot of work in, and the getting of a Yopon and other shrubs.
There was a whole lot of community feeling in those days.
But at that point I would say probably everybody
whose children went to that school was either a faculty or staff member at Texas A&M?
I believe it was, yes.
There were many of the, that's right, faculty or staff members, yes.
That's a good way to put it.
There were some folks from the dairy, there were certain dairy families, dairy production, milk production families, their children went to Consolidated.
You mentioned
something about either getting the road paved to Bryan or else having to have another grocery store.
Did you get that other grocery store?
We wound up having a grocery store on... We didn't wind up.
We had already inveigled the faculty, I mean the management, the Department of Physical Plants, what's now Physical Plants.
I put in a store right next to Milner Hall and they did a big business and it was very convenient and helpful.
Then the other grocery store that we were talking about was at South Gate and resulted from that incorporation as a
incorporated municipality.
The store that was on the campus, how long was that in existence?
About 10 years, if I can remember correctly.
Did that start in 38 or 39?
It was in the 30s.
In the 30s that it started.
So it carried what, a general line of groceries it would be?
Yes, and bought from wholesale from what was then
the Howell Wholesale Grocery.
But it was, I would think that would have been kind of a unique situation where the university or the college would run its own.
Well, the college really didn't have only an indirect control over it in the least, but it put in for the help of the faculty.
And I was one of, with Pete Butler and Burgess and
I missed the printer.
We needed also a place where men could cash checks at odd hours, which were then odd hours, and we put in, for that purpose, organized a little state bank in 1946.
Where was it located?
It was located in a wooden shack behind where
Homer Adams held his insurance store.
What became of that bank?
It is now the University National Bank.
It became the University National.
We had on the campus with Dr. I.P.
Trotter as president, and I think it resulted in an assistant to the clerk, and we had the faculty loan
and discount organizations on the campus.
And when we got together and organized that bank, we allowed the bank to buy up that little faculty loan association.
Get a mental block now and then.
Uh-huh.
I can remember that Dr. I.P.
Trotter and I, as his assistant, had to close it out, and Mrs. Bower
was also one of the last to give up.
That was for your loan associate, faculty loan association.
But you sold that out to the University National Bank.
Yes.
Was that always its name or did it have a...
It started out as the College Station State Bank, 1946.
And we had a, which you may not want, we had a up and down
kaleidoscopic career for the first five years, which you might have heard of.
No, I hadn't heard it.
Well, after about three years, we had an executive vice president, which I won't name, who decided to make a loan of $40,000 to a man who was
didn't have too good a record to buy pipe.
And to close the Second World War, about 1948-9, pipe was to be bought from a man in Dallas who didn't really possess the pipe.
And the money, instead of being put in, and I'll put this in writing, instead of being handled in telegraph,
was handled by telephone by the executive vice president.
And when it got to the big bank in Dallas, this man owed them more money than the amount a pipe cost, and their money was gone to seed.
Another case of a big dog eating a little dog.
We went to suit and got back half of it.
and everybody out of $38 a share, I mean out of $26 a share, counting the stock and the reserve, everybody put up $12 gladly and surprised all the state banking department in Austin by being
we all our directors met over there in Austin on a Saturday including Dr. Pete Butler and Herschel Burgess and myself and had the money raised by Monday and now I have over
17 million below the line.
I take it you have continued your connection with the University National Bank then?
Yes, my interest in it continues.
I guess you'd call it a director.
You're still on the board of directors of the bank?
At the age of 80.
But you were one of the founders of it?
Yes, the first president of it.
Because it couldn't get anybody else to take it.
Back to a little bit to your service on the city council in the city of College Station.
I believe that was for, I believe I picked up seven years, which would have begun in 1938 or 39.
those must have been some pretty important years since that was when the city was actually incorporated or was created.
You, I imagine, had to do a lot of planning, did you not?
We did indeed and we had to be very careful of promises and when big arguments took place between dwellers on
one of the best streets, such as Lee Street, and the dwellers on, what's the name of the general?
First big general.
Pershing?
Pershing Street, on whether the alley should preserve its trees or should have trees cut so as to permit the entrance and exit of the garbage pickup truck
the council had some very grave problems to handle.
Sometimes members of the council would go out and and help open up certain areas and some of the busiest times was when the council almost overlapped with the school board and you had to try to
get room for gravel and for pavement, for sidewalks at least, and for housing for some of the teachers in the school.
Dr. Clark deserves credit for having started
the first housing plan in College Station.
And this is F.B.
Clark?
Yep, F.B.
Clark.
And it was very difficult in 1926 for a professor of poultry husbandry to get a loan locally to build a house, and he had to go to Houston Building and Loan to get his loan.
But later that opened up very
Well, indeed, because the teaching staff during the Depression had a type of person that paid every month on the doc.
But it was hard money.
And you got a faculty member that made $2,000.
He thought he was riding high.
Yeah, I can imagine, because there were a lot of people that weren't making anything.
Yes.
We weren't making anything.

And one of the daughters, the daughters of one of our eminent men on the campus, one of the deans, married one of the most promising of our graduates here, who opened up a series of service stations in Memphis, which looked like one of the most productive jobs in the world.
wound up having to service his own station, and she said that a person that had a job on the A&M faculty that gave him at least $1,800 really didn't know how lucky he was.
She was the daughter of a dean.
Those depression years produced a type of man that we wonder now what kind of
individuals we have that can get on welfare and won't need to work.
You can eliminate that, maybe.
Well, I think you're not at all alone in making that comment.
It's a fairly widely held belief and I think with some justification.
doubt, though, that you would seriously advocate that we come back to the Depression era?
We give welfare in the amount that is given and Social Security.
We wouldn't come back to a place like we had in 1932.
And we have friends who have read
White, not Stuart Edward White, but the other White, who was the originator of Cornell University.
Ezra Cornell got Dr. White to map out the foundation of Cornell in 1868, and he wrote a
